<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="18378a9e4585879a965632934553541e" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Curse of the Black Numenorean<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.78)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15060'>Matthew "Wedge772" Ting</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=15060&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 12, 2004</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Corsairs of the Caribbean: The Curse of the Black Numenorean<br />
************************************************************<br />
<br />
1. Introduction (i.e. The Boring Bits)<br />
<br />
So here I am, sitting at work, pretending to be busy, waiting patiently for my first chance to play a game with the new Siege of Gondor cards, when I realise just how little has really been discussed about how the new Corsair subculture could potentially work. &quot;But surely &#39;tis better to wait and play with the actual cards!&quot; you might say, but nay! For I am impatient, and bored, and need a submission to rate other peoples stuff anyway.<br />
<br />
Anyway, I&#39;ve seen some discussion that describes these guys absolutely powerful. I&#39;ve seen people agree with that point of view, comparing the power of Corsairs to the power of Wargs or Knights, before we actually got around to playing them (those Wargs sure did change the meta! See how many people stock Arrow-Slits because they&#39;re afraid of them?). Some have likened them to the bizarre lovechild of Moria/Dunlendings. Let&#39;s see if we can make some sense of them...<br />
<br />
2. The Cards (Those Mangy Sea Dogs)<br />
<br />
Going over the cards, one might tend to notice a few themes that run throughout this entire subculture. Firstly, all the cards are yellow. Secondly, there&#39;s a heavy reliance on possessions that play to the support area, and hardly any conditions or events. Finally, there&#39;s this whole deal with Raider tokens (henceforth known as &quot;loot&quot;). <br />
<br />
2a. The Looters<br />
<br />
First, let&#39;s have a look at the ways to take loot and load up our ships.<br />
<br />
Castamir of Umbar (8R51) - 7/14/4<br />
Exert this guy (making him more powerful), to play a guy to add 2 tokens to a card that already has one. Depending on who you play with him, you should be able to get 2 more tokens off that corsair too. 4 tokens for playing someone? Not a bad trade at all! Only weakness there is those minions must come from hand, not from the discard pile with Black Sails of Umbar, and that each exertion brings him one step nearer to being shot to death. But hey, if he survives all that he&#39;s tougher. <br />
<br />
Corsair Buccaneer (8C53) - 3/8/2<br />
Play this guy and remove a threat to add 2 tokens. Simple, easy. Unless you plan on adding some ways to add threats, which just dilutes the purpose of your pirates, this guy means tokens at City Gates (site 5) or Dagorlad (site 9). Certainly more efficient use of those threats than removing them 1 for 1 for tokens on your Ships of Great Draught. <br />
<br />
Corsair Freebooter (8C54) - 3/8/2<br />
A far more specialised breed of looter, this one isn&#39;t going to see as much use. Commonly seen Free Peoples cards using culture tokens would include Fortress Never Fallen (which does little against Corsairs anyway due to lack of conditions), We Left None Alive (handy, alot of these guys are easily exhausted by a horse), Ithilien Trap (which would have been quite easily charged up against smaller pirates) or Garrison of Osgiliath (also fairly handy). You could also make someone cry and remove tokens from Final Count (&quot;... and suddenly Legolas lost count, and all were confused...&quot;). Probably the best use for this guy would be to remove tokens from your own Corsair War Galleys, and place them on other ships where those tokens can actually be used. Of course, you don&#39;t actually gain any tokens overall by doing this.<br />
<br />
Corsair Lookout (8U56) - 1/5/1<br />
&quot;Elrond off the starboard bow!&quot;. This time, you need initiative, but you get to discard (i.e: make them walk the plank) an ally for 2 tokens. With attributes of 5/1, he&#39;s not going to live long, but luckily he doesn&#39;t need to. Initiative is ridiculously easy for Corsairs to obtain with Corsair War Galley or even Harsh Tongues. Immediately, initiative stops the discarding abilities of Deor or Gondorian Merchant. Getting rid of that Elrond, or Bounder, or Leowyn, or perhaps Tom Bombadil, is always a good thing; getting tokens for it is even better.<br />
 <br />
Corsair Marauder (8R57) - 4/9/2<br />
Probably the most useful of the looters, spot another corsair and discard a possession to add 2 tokens. And people thought Ulaire Cantea, Faster Than Winds was good! Obvious first targets would be cards like Aragorn&#39;s Bow, Merry&#39;s Sword, or mounts. Getting rid of Rohan mounts is always a good thing; against Eomer with Firefoot and Eomer&#39;s Spear, that&#39;s 1 less minion he can take on, 2 less strength he&#39;ll gain, and 2 less damage he&#39;ll cause, allowing your corsair to survive the skirmish (a point which will be brought up again later). Possession removal is always good.<br />
<br />
Corsair Plunderer (8C58) - 2/6/2<br />
Arguably the meat-and-potatoes corsair, play him to discard 2 cards from hand to add 2 tokens. The most reliable of the Corsairs, he doesn&#39;t care what your opponent has or has not played, and he helps your card flow tremendously. Drop 1 or 2 of these guys at site 8 to clear out your Free Peoples cards for the move to 9. With 4 copies of this guy in a deck, the Corsair deck can afford to be a bit more swollen than most decks.<br />
<br />
Ships of Great Draught (8R65)<br />
A ship that can load itself? For the cost of a threat or a Raider card discarded from hand, you get a token on this ship. Use up those 3 threats from the City Gates with Buccaneers, and whatever is left with these. Coupled with Plunderers, again you gain an incredible card discarding capability, to set up your Free Peoples side.<br />
<br />
2b. Enjoying Your Plunder<br />
<br />
So now you have a whole bunch of tokens on your loaded ships, it&#39; time to eat, drink, and be merry! But, umm... how?<br />
<br />
Corsair War Galley (8U59)<br />
As we&#39;ve seen, getting tokens is pretty easy. Now, with a War Galley out, 6 bits of treasure and a Raider minion on the deck, you get initiative regardless of the Free Peoples hand! It even starts you off with a token to get you started. Having initiative is always better than not having it; even if you don&#39;t make use of that yourself (which you should with Corsair Lookout or Black Numenorean), it stops the Free Peoples player from using any initiative based text. To top it off, you can ditch the thing in the regroup to add 1 twilight for each token you can spot. Ditching 1 or 2 War Galleys at site 8 could mean a very hairy double to site 9; at any other site, it could be a great way to convince your opponent to stop. <br />
<br />
Black Numenorean (8R49) - 6/12/3<br />
So now we have initiative, we can pay some loot (remove a Raider token) to discard a possession from a guy he&#39;s skirmishing. To top it off, he&#39;s also fierce. It&#39;s nearly impossible to beat this guy without pumps, and one of these guys sitting around will certainly discourage a double move.<br />
<br />
Black Sails of Umbar (8C50)<br />
Probably my favourite card from the subculture, ditch it to play a corsair from your discard pile for -X, where X is the amount of loot sitting on it. Minion recursion and hand extension, this is the card that makes Corsair swarming a possibility. If you can manage 4 of these on the table, ditch one to grab a minion who adds tokens; ditch the next to grab a minion at -3 cost (1 token when you played the Black Sail, 2 tokens from the first minion). Repeat, and you&#39;ll have several minions out at hardly any twilight cost. Or better yet, grab a Castamir with the first Black Sails (for 6 twilight), and play minions from hand to add even more tokens to the sails, to grab out even more and/or bigger corsairs. Much like Moria swarms, this requires extensive set-up for a swarm at one site. Whilst it lacks the card drawing/twilight adding of Goblin Scimitars with Goblin Armouries, possessions are safer than conditions in the support area, and you&#39;re getting twilight reductions and your pick of minions from the discard pile anyway, without the need to discard 3 cards from hand.<br />
<br />
Corsair Ballista (8C52)<br />
A strength +2 weapon for 0 twilight cost ain&#39;t bad; but while you have initiative, that minion is also an archer and fierce. Unlesss you plan on making your deck cause plenty of archery wounds, again diluting the Corsair deck, that 1 archery (read: wound on Frodo) will do little. Being fierce doesn&#39;t help much, your big fighters (the Castamir and Black Numenorean) are already fierce, and it also just makes Arwen, Fair Elf Maiden kill them off more easily, or Eomer to take them on in the fierce skirmish. Perhaps I&#39;m wrong, but I don&#39;t see much benefit from this. <br />
<br />
Corsair Gunners (8C55) 5/10/3<br />
Same argument goes with this guy as goes with the Ballista; if you have initiative, remove a token to make a Corsair fierce. Whilst it could be useful to make an entire swarm of Corsairs all fierce (with a big &quot;Ha-ha!&quot; to Aragorn, Ranger Of The North), I&#39;m afraid I just don&#39;t see all that much benefit. Corsairs in general don&#39;t look to me to be big skirmish winners, unlike Nazgul or Dunland. They get rid of cards in the Shadow phase, and potentially swarm out with the Black Sails. <br />
<br />
Ships of Great Draught (8R65)<br />
We&#39;ve seen how this ship can load itself and help card flow, now let&#39;s see what it does by itself. Regroup phase, ditch 2 tokens here to take a Raider card (note: *any* Raider card, not necessarily corsair related) from your discard pile to top of your draw deck. Don&#39;t forget to discard your Corsair War Galley first, and your opponent will definitely think twice about double moving. &quot;So, umm... I add 8 twilight during regroup... and I&#39;ll go grab this Easterling Captain here... moving on?&quot;. Could potentially be useful in a non-corsair Raider deck, to help set up combos like Easterling Captain/Easterling Polearm/Raider Bow. Also a great way to ensure certain cards will be available to you at site 9, or site 8 if you force them to move with Osgiliath Channel (when you can lay a beat-down with twilight added from Corsair War Galleys and your choice of cards to draw with Ships of Great Draught).<br />
<br />
Wind That Sped Ships (8C66)<br />
A pumper that makes a corsair strength +1 for each Raider token, limit 6, and can return to the top of your draw deck if you have initiative, all for 1 twilight? As far as pumpers go, don&#39;t look any further for your corsairs, this one is a real steal (pun intended). Whether or not pumps are appropriate in a swarm deck is questionable, but it could definitely help the Castamir or Black Numenorean overwhelm a companion. Be careful when putting it back onto your deck, that you&#39;re not depriving yourself the chance to draw good Free Peoples cards on your turn, or enough minions against a double move.<br />
<br />
<br />
3. Other Cards That Might Be Handy/Fun<br />
<br />
Harsh Tongues (7C150)/Rout (7R158)<br />
So long as you can get 1 Raider token on Harsh Tongues, it should be easy to get 2 more during your next Shadow phase and gain permanent initiative, rather than just while you can spot a Raider man. The benefit of this is you get to use Rout; each time the fellowship moves when you have initiative, exert 2 companions. Corsairs are probably the culture which can most easily set this up, and with 4 copies of Rout out, the Free Peoples player needs to exert 8 times to move (take that, Under The Watching Eye!). The problem is, suddenly your deck becomes reliant on conditions, meaning Legolas, Dauntless Hunter and all forms of condition removal will hurt your deck.<br />
<br />
Raider Bow (7C155)/Red Wrath (7U157) or Whirling Strike (4C260)<br />
Being Raider men, Corsairs can make just as much use of this combo as can Southrons or Easterlings. Coupled with initiative gained from Corsair War Galleys and Desert Runner/Scout/Sneak (7C133, 7U134, 7C135), you could have an effective wounding deck on your hands. However, this sort of deck is already highly combo intensive, and coupling with Corsairs makes it even more complicated. Best to stick to Easterling Captains with Polearms. Not every Raider deck requires these cards; however, the threat of them alone may well influence how your opponent assigns your minions.<br />
<br />
Discovered (4R223)<br />
Exert a minion to ditch a condition in the maneuver phase? Sure, why not!<br />
<br />
Haradwaith (8C61)<br />
Initiative at site 4K regardless is a handy thing, just in case you haven&#39;t gotten yourself set up yet. However, the ability to add 5 twilight when your opponent plays a companion is very nice... it could make them think twice about playing an extra companion, making the swarm easier to pull off or even just clogging their hand.<br />
<br />
Fierce In Despair (7R148)<br />
This could be one of my favourite cards to combo with Corsairs; all I need is 2 of them to survive till regroup, I can ditch a Corsair War Galley for twilight, and I get to discard a companion. Discarding key starting companions is often as good as killing them if there is no way to get them back into play. Getting rid of companions is always helpful to set up a swarm as well. The only problem is getting your minions to survive until regroup, which is why I advocate avoiding making them fierce, and getting rid of bows/mounts as quickly as possible with your Marauders.<br />
<br />
Great Beats (7C149)<br />
Again, I can use Corsair War Galleys to set up twilight in the regroup phase; but if I have 3 guys left and 9 pool sitting around, chances are the Free Peoples player wasn&#39;t going to double anyway.<br />
<br />
Put Forth His Strength (7R205)<br />
A Ringwraith/Corsair combo deck could be interesting, using this card as an alternative win condition. Looking at the criteria, the Corsairs can easily gain initiative, and moving into site 9 Dagorlad ensures 3 threats. All you need after that is a way to add 3 burdens and kill 3 companions/allies, before site 9, and to spot a Nazgul. Killing allies with Tower Assassin (2R93) or Their Power Is In Terror (1U226) would be the easiest way, or going for a beatdown strategy with Castamirs, Black Numenoreans and Nazgul. Ulaire Attea, Wraith on Wings (7R210) can even add 2 burdens during the Shadow phase while you have initiative, and spot another Ringwraith minion (perhaps the Morgul Lurker, 8C76, who will add 2 to archery with initiative?). It&#39;s certainly not the best deck in the world, or possibly even viable, but I&#39;d love to see someone try and pull it off!<br />
<br />
4. So How Does The Corsair Deck Perform?<br />
<br />
How would I know? I haven&#39;t playtested the thing! :p However, my thoughts would be that the deck has swarm potential once set up, and in the meantime the capability to cycle through your deck and discard certain cards of your opponent. I&#39;d also say this is a Shadow side with definite stopping power, if you add twilight in the regroup with Corsair War Galleys, and take cards back from the discard with Ships of Great Draught. Big minions like the Castamir and Black Numenorean further discourage doubling. <br />
<br />
Strengths: Card flow, discarding opponents cards (including possessions), swarm capabilities from discard and at a discount, a few big bruisers, twilight generation (during regroup), and not relying on conditions that can be discarded.<br />
<br />
Weaknesses: The deck needs to set itself up. The sooner you&#39;re swimming in tokens the better, and there should be no real reason why you can&#39;t do it quickly... but you never know. Archery/directed wounding also hurts, with no form of prevention (without splashing other subcultures, like Gollum with Sweeter Meats or Southrons with mounts and Line of Defense). However, most of your minions are vitality 2 or 3, making them harder to take down than your average Moria swarm can be taken down with archery. Gorgoroth Servitor (8U100) may well be a good idea to stack as a splash minion, if your meta is archery heavy (like mine is!). Possession removal is also painful, but you&#39;re not likely to see more than 2 or 3 Arrow Slits per deck, probably only 1 or 2 Roll of Thunder (if any). So, where is our Corsair who removes tokens to prevent wounds, or to save possessions?<br />
<br />
5. Specific Free Peoples Matchups<br />
<br />
Rohan: Don&#39;t expect to win many skirmishes, except with your bruisers or with pumps. Discarding mounts during the Shadow phase is key here, and if you can discard Eomer with Fierce in Despair, you&#39;re doing well! Once set-up, you should be able to swarm a Rohan player. Otherwise, discarding possessions with Black Numenoreans/Corsair Marauders will slowly leave them vulnerable.<br />
<br />
Gondor/Elf: A bad match, this deck uses both archery/direct wounding and some good size companions to kill your guys off. Hope to discard Aragorn&#39;s Bow ASAP with a Marauder, and wear down their fellowship with large minions and swarms, or stop them from doubling with the threat of a swarm. Discarding Elrond with Corsair Lookout should be fun :)<br />
<br />
Dauntless Hunter/choke in general: Lack of conditions or events will be a major advantage to you, as your deck loses nothing and does not suffer from hand clog with Corsair Plunderers helping to cycle. Get your Black Sails set up and go for the swarm, and hope their undirected archery isn&#39;t enough to kill you. Should be a good matchup. <br />
<br />
Army of the Dead: Without seeing exactly how these decks will work, I suspect losing initiative for Swept Away will be a game breaker in this matchup. A bunch of exhausted Wraiths and a ton of threats could be painful.<br />
<br />
Gimli/Slaked Thirts: Tricky matchup, expect most or all of your minions to die horribly. Play similarly to a Gondor/Elf matchup and hope for the best!<br />
<br />
6. The Right Free Peoples Side to Pair With<br />
<br />
From what I can tell, the Corsair shadow is likely to be somewhat big (potentially 35-40 cards), similar to Moria. Therefore, you need to couple it with a Free Peoples side that won&#39;t clog up your hand and cycles well, without needing any particular cards early in the game. Rohan has always been a decent matchup for such decks, and has the added advantage of being able to run to 9 if it looks like the Corsairs just aren&#39;t being effective at stopping/killing your opponent. Gimli/Slaked Thirsts decks can also cycle extremely well, given cards like Ever My Heart Rises to further set up the Free Peoples side. Cards top-decked to Ever My Heart Rises can be brought back with Ships of Great Draught if necessary, otherwise just hope nothing important gets stacked onto it. Avoid Gonder/Elf or Dauntless Hunter pairings, they prefer smaller and tighter decks. Decks such as Ringbound Rangers could well be a disaster, again requiring a tight deck and without the ability to cycle as well as others (especially with Pippin returning to hand).<br />
<br />
7. Conclusions<br />
<br />
I can&#39;t conclude anything, but from what I can see, I believe these guys have potential to be viable at least, competitive potentially. Time and experience will see how well these guys do. In the meantime, lunch break! <br></font><BR><font class="bfont"> <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?id=5440&view=1&PHPSESSID=18378a9e4585879a965632934553541e'>Read the Reviews</a><font class="bfont"> | <A HREF='/lotr/articles/articles.php?PHPSESSID=18378a9e4585879a965632934553541e'>Back to List</A></font><p><font class="bfont"> <b>You must be a member to contribute to Decktech.</b>  <p>Please <a href='/lotr/main/join.php?PHPSESSID=18378a9e4585879a965632934553541e'> become a registered member</a></font></font></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_09.gif"></td></tr>
